article.headline: Running game keys 2nd highest point total
article.linkText: Shock hits rare triple figures in win
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Detroit Shock head coach Bill Laimbeer promised before the season that his squad would somehow be able to combine a big frontcourt with a run-and-gun style. On Thursday, his team proved him right. Swin Cash scored 23 points and Deanna Nolan added 17 Thursday as the Shock beating Connecticut 103-89. "I think you saw today what this team is about," Laimbeer said. "We are strong in the post, and we can run up and down the court. We came into this game thinking we could outrun Connecticut, and we proved that." Detroit's point total was the second-highest in team history, trailing a league-record 111 points against Indiana on June 18, 2000. The Shock outrebounded the Sun 45-24 and had as many offensive rebounds (14) as Connecticut had on the defensive end. "It all starts with rebounding for us," said Cash, who played just 27 minutes. "People look at our size and think we are going to be a half-court team, but we have big players who can get up and down the floor. We are still fine-tuning things, but this is what we are going to be like." The Shock are now 1-1 after last year's 0-13 start and became the first WNBA team this season to score 100 points in a game. "They played well and we didn't," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "They outworked us, they outrebounded us and they basically outplayed us in every facet of the game." Shannon Johnson led Connecticut with 24 points, but only scored one basket in the second half. Nykesha Sales had 20 for the Sun while Adrienne Johnson added 14. Ruth Riley had 14 points for Detroit while rookie Cheryl Ford added 10 points and 12 rebounds. Ford had six points and nine rebounds in the second half. "She's an aggressive player," Laimbeer said of Ford, the daughter of NBA Karl Malone a one-time playing rival of Laimbeer. "I didn't give her much of a chance in the first half, and everyone was playing so well that she didn't (have) many chances on the offensive end, but she played defense and rebounded." The Shock led 51-45 at the half, despite the 22 points from Johnson. Cash had 13 for Detroit, which fell just two points short of a team record for first-half points. Detroit expanded its lead to 15 by scoring the first nine points of the second half, capped by a Nolan 3-pointer. Connecticut came back with an 11-2 run, including six points from Jessie Hicks, but Cash answered with a 3-pointer to put Detroit up 67-58. The Shock put the game away with a 10-0 run that put them up 81-62 with 12:30 to play. Game notes
Connecticut played without forward Wendy Palmer (neck) and guard Katie Douglas (heel). ... The game was played at 11 a.m. and drew a crowd of 12,414 fans, mostly kids. The attendance was the sixth-largest in Shock history. ... The Sun set a franchise record for most points allowed, including their days in Orlando.
